{"title_page": "D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (company)", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S. company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Deja Vu Services, Inc.\n| logo                = DEJAVU 01.jpg\n| logo_size           = \n| logo_padding        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| former_names        = Deja Vu Consulting, Inc. / Deja Vu, Inc.\n| type                = Strip clubs and adult retail stores\n| industry            = [[Adult entertainment]]\n| founded             = {{start date and age|1968}}\n| founder             = [[Harry Mohney]]\n| hq_location         = \n| hq_location_city    = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| num_locations       = 168\n| area_served         = International\n| key_people          = \n| products            = \n| brands              = Deja Vu Showgirls, Hustler Club, Dream Girls, Little Darlings, Buck's Cabaret, Penthouse Club, Gold Club, Gay '90s, Love Boutique, Adult Emporium, Pleasure Emporium, & Many Others\n| revenue             = $400M+ (annually)\n| owner               = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees       = 8,300\n| website             = http://dejavu.com\n}}\n[[File:Hustlerclublasvegas.jpg|thumb|Hustler Club in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]]]]\n\n'''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Services, Inc.''' is an American company that ({{As of|2017|lc=on}}) operates about 132 [[strip club]]s in 41 U.S. states, as well as multiple clubs in the United Kingdom, Australia, France, Canada, and Mexico.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dejavu.com|title=Home|newspaper=Deja Vu Showgirls|access-date=2016-12-17}}</ref>  The company also operates a large chain of adult retail stores, multiple popular adult websites and production studios, gay bars, nightclubs, karaoke bars, restaurants, and has substantial real estate holdings. It is the largest strip club operator in the world, and one of the largest adult businesses in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dejavu.com|title=Home|work=dejavu.com|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hustlerclubs.com|title=Home|work=hustlerclubs.com|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref>  In 2016, the group opened Deja Vu Showgirls Tijuana, the largest adult entertainment club in the world, at over {{convert|140,000|sqft|m2|0}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dejavutijuana.com/|title=#1 GENTLEMEN'S CLUB IN THE WORLD - D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Showgirls Tijuana|website=dejavutijuana.com|access-date=2016-12-17}}</ref>  It also operates the second largest adult club in the world, Larry Flynt's Hustler Club in Las Vegas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vegashustlerclub.com/|title=Best Las Vegas Strip Club {{!}} Strip Clubs Las Vegas|website=vegashustlerclub.com|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-17}}</ref>\n\nThe company is headquartered in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]; it was founded and is controlled by [[Harry Mohney]], who partners with [[Roger Forbes]] and [[Larry Flynt]].  He opened his first D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu strip club in the [[Lake City, Seattle|Lake City]] neighborhood of [[Seattle]] in 1985.  Many of the original clubs were converted adult theaters.  Mohney had a humble beginning as a projectionist at a drive-in movie theater in Durand, Michigan, later converted the failing enterprise into the infamous \"Durand Dirties,\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Beast Article|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/the-big-daddy-of-drive-in-porn-theaters}}</ref> and eventually grew the chain to about 300 adult theaters nationally.  An elusive man often referred to as the \"[[Howard Hughes]] of Porn,\" Mohney was the largest distributor of [[pornography]] from the late '60s to the mid '90s,<ref>{{cite web|title=10 News Article|url=http://www.10news.com/news/10news-exposes-san-diego-s-king-of-strip-clubs-}}</ref> grossing nearly $1 billion in the distribution business between 1970 and 1998.  That business largely concluded with Mohney serving three years in federal prison for tax-related crimes.<ref>{{cite web|title=MLive Article|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2011/06/mohneys_ties.html}}</ref>  While he was indicted dozens of times on federal charges, this was the only charge that ever resulted in a conviction.\n\nThe strip clubs are called \"D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Showgirls,\" \"Little Darlings,\" \"Dream Girls,\" or (by agreement with Mohney's long-time friend [[Larry Flynt]], who is not involved in the management of the clubs) \"Larry Flynt's Hustler Club\" and \"Hustler Barely Legal\". D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu also owns all of the adult theaters and clubs in [[San Francisco]], most being on Broadway; these, however, carry different names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sfweekly.com/thesnitch/2013/08/lusty_lady_deja_vu.php|work=SF Weekly|title=Lusty Lady Closure Creates S.F. Strip Club Monopoly for Seattle-Based Business|author=Chris Roberts|date=August 21, 2013}}</ref> In 2012 D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu opened a club in collaboration with [[Vince Neil]] (of the rock band [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]) in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], appropriately named \"Vince Neil's Girls, Girls, Girls.\"  D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu has monopolies or near-monopolies in many areas, including San Francisco, Washington State, and Tijuana, Mexico.  Further, it also operates many clubs that do not carry its typical brand names, as well as the Erotic Heritage Museum in Las Vegas, Nevada.\n\nThe clubs typically aim for a clean and upscale atmosphere and offer fully nude or topless stage dancing as well as [[lap dance]]s. Many do not serve alcohol, to avoid stringent liquor license requirements. Several clubs have associated \"D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Love Boutique\" stores selling sex toys, lingerie, adult DVDs, D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu merchandise, cigars, etc. There are also several stand-lone boutique locations, many of which are the largest stores in the country. The chain organizes nationwide club competitions such as \"D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Showgirl of the Year\", \"Showgirl Spectacular\", and \"Pole Princess.\"\n[[File:Ldlv.jpg|thumb|Little Darlings in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]]]]\nD\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu published the adult magazine ''Showgirls'' from 1990 to 2002. Issue #1 was published in October 1990 and the magazine ran monthly until November 2002. In 2002 the magazine published four quarterly editions until it ceased publication in the fall of that year. ''Showgirls'' magazine featured nude layouts of dancers from D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Showgirls clubs, as well as adult film stars; strip club reviews; coverage of events ranging from new club openings to adult film conventions, to special events like Mardi Gras, Daytona Beach and Myrtle Beach Bike weeks and more; erotic stories; adult video reviews and adult industry legal news. Many of adult film's top performers have appeared on its pages and covers, including [[Jenna Jameson]], [[Tera Patrick]], and [[Serenity (actress)|Serenity]], who also served as the magazine's \"guest publisher\" from November 1997 to the fall of 2002.\n\nD\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu has sponsored many sporting events such as charity golf outings, unlimited hydroplane (speedboat) racing, off-road truck racer Gene Woods and female funny car driver Leah Pruett Leduc.  Its publicity stunts at various clubs often garner international media attention.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/las-vegas-strip-club-recruits-high-school-graduates-article-1.2250427]</ref>\n\nDancers in the clubs typically have the legal status of [[independent contractor]]s.  The company is also known for having owned various businesses that set various landmark First Amendment Supreme Court decisions, including ''[[Miller v. California]]'', ''[[Marks v. United States]]'', ''[[City of Los Angeles v. Alameda Books, Inc.]],'' and ''[[Barnes v. Glen Theatre, Inc.|Barnes v. Glen Theater, Inc.]]''\n\n==Awards==\n*1998 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-1998|title= The 1998 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140626011223/http://edpublications.com/award-winners-1998|archive-date= 2014-06-26|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n*1999 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club of the Year (Midwest Nude Clubs) \u2013 [[Lansing]], [[Michigan]]<ref name=EDA1999>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-1999|title= The 1999 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*1999 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club of the Year (Southwest Nude Clubs) \u2013 [[Ontario, California]]<ref name=EDA1999/>\n*1999 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Industry Innovator of the Year \u2013 [[Harry Mohney]]<ref name=EDA1999/>\n*2000 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2000|title= The 2000 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2001 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref name=EDA2001>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2001|title= The 2001 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2001 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club of the Year (Northwest Topless and Nude Clubs) \u2013 [[Seattle, Washington]]<ref name=EDA2001/>\n*2002 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2002|title= The 2002 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2003 Exotic Dancer Hall of Fame \u2013 [[Harry Mohney]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2003|title= The 2003 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2004 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2004|title= The 2004 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2006 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2006|title= The 2006 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140626005531/http://edpublications.com/award-winners-2006|archive-date= 2014-06-26|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n*2008 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref name=EDA2008>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2008|title= The 2008 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2008 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 General Manager of the Year (Southwest) \u2013 Sherry Cooper ([[Industry, California]])<ref name=EDA2008/>\n*2008 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Overall General Manager of the Year \u2013 Sherry Cooper (Industry, California)<ref name=EDA2008/>\n*2008 Exotic Dancer Hall of Fame \u2013 Jim St. John<ref name=EDA2008/>\n*2008 [[Free Speech Coalition|FSC]] Legacy Award \u2013 [[Harry Mohney]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://business.avn.com/articles/legal/FSC-Announces-Election-2008-Gala-Fundraiser-53471.html|title= FSC Announces 'Election 2008' Gala Fundraiser|accessdate= 2014-08-21|author= David Sullivan|date= 2008-06-30|magazine= [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]}}</ref>\n*2009 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2009|title= The 2009 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2010 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://business.avn.com/articles/video/Exotic-Dancer-Awards-Names-2010-Winners-409665.html|title= Exotic Dancer Awards Names 2010 Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|author= Steve Javors|date= 2010-08-25|magazine= [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]}}</ref>\n*2011 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Small Club of the Year (Southeast) \u2013 [[Nashville]], [[Tennessee]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2011|title= The 2011 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2012 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.xbiz.com/news/153591|title= Exotic Dancer Publications Announces 2012 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|author= Chad Mayer|date= 2012-09-05|publisher= [[XBIZ]]}}</ref>\n*2013 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Small Club of the Year (Midwest) \u2013 [[Lansing]], [[Michigan]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://business.avn.com/articles/video/ED-s-Exotic-Dancer-Awards-Show-Announces-Winners-527388.html|title= ED\u2019s Exotic Dancer Awards Show Announces Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|date= 2013-08-28|magazine= [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [http://wafreepress.org/31/Dancers.html Sex Trade Workers Organize], by Rebecca Kavoussi\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080719025215/http://www.thef-wordzine.com/harpies_stripping505.html Stripping, a First Hand Account]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060408075903/http://www.exoticdancerslib.com/phpBB-2/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?p=241&sid=5fd13fa8a0e6991d7823a102e3b1a4af Collection of newspaper articles about Harry Mohney]\n* [http://www.sandiegoreader.com/weblogs/bands/2008/oct/23/battle-of-the-peeps---an-insider-history-of-san-di/ Battle of the Peeps], by Jay Allen Sanford\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100207042839/http://sfist.com/2005/12/12/justice_for_strippers.php Justice for Strippers], SFist, 2005-12-12\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.dejavu.com D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu main site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deja Vu (Company)}}\n[[Category:Strip clubs]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Lansing, Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|U.S. company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Deja Vu Services, Inc.\