ng three years in federal prison for tax-related crimes.<ref>{{cite web|title=MLive Article|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2011/06/mohneys_ties.html}}</ref>  While he was indicted dozens of times on federal charges, this was the only charge that ever resulted in a conviction.\n\nThe strip clubs are called \"D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Showgirls,\" \"Little Darlings,\" \"Dream Girls,\" or (by agreement with Mohney's long-time friend [[Larry Flynt]], who is not involved in the management of the clubs) \"Larry Flynt's Hustler Club\" and \"Hustler Barely Legal\". D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu also owns all of the adult theaters and clubs in [[San Francisco]], most being on Broadway; these, however, carry different names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sfweekly.com/thesnitch/2013/08/lusty_lady_deja_vu.php|work=SF Weekly|title=Lusty Lady Closure Creates S.F. Strip Club Monopoly for Seattle-Based Business|author=Chris Roberts|date=August 21, 2013}}</ref> In 2012 D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu opened a club in collaboration with [[Vince Neil]] (of the rock band [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]) in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], appropriately named \"Vince Neil's Girls, Girls, Girls.\"  D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu has monopolies or near-monopolies in many areas, including San Francisco, Washington State, and Tijuana, Mexico.  Further, it also operates many clubs that do not carry its typical brand names, as well as the Erotic Heritage Museum in Las Vegas, Nevada.\n\nThe clubs typically aim for a clean and upscale atmosphere and offer fully nude or topless stage dancing as well as [[lap dance]]s. Many do not serve alcohol, to avoid stringent liquor license requirements. Several clubs have associated \"D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Love Boutique\" stores selling sex toys, lingerie, adult DVDs, D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu merchandise, cigars, etc. There are also several stand-lone boutique locations, many of which are the largest stores in the country. The chain organizes nationwide club competitions such as \"D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Showgirl of the Year\", \"Showgirl Spectacular\", and \"Pole Princess.\"\n[[File:Ldlv.jpg|thumb|Little Darlings in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]]]]\nD\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu published the adult magazine ''Showgirls'' from 1990 to 2002. Issue #1 was published in October 1990 and the magazine ran monthly until November 2002. In 2002 the magazine published four quarterly editions until it ceased publication in the fall of that year. ''Showgirls'' magazine featured nude layouts of dancers from D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Showgirls clubs, as well as adult film stars; strip club reviews; coverage of events ranging from new club openings to adult film conventions, to special events like Mardi Gras, Daytona Beach and Myrtle Beach Bike weeks and more; erotic stories; adult video reviews and adult industry legal news. Many of adult film's top performers have appeared on its pages and covers, including [[Jenna Jameson]], [[Tera Patrick]], and [[Serenity (actress)|Serenity]], who also served as the magazine's \"guest publisher\" from November 1997 to the fall of 2002.\n\nD\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu has sponsored many sporting events such as charity golf outings, unlimited hydroplane (speedboat) racing, off-road truck racer Gene Woods and female funny car driver Leah Pruett Leduc.  Its publicity stunts at various clubs often garner international media attention.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/las-vegas-strip-club-recruits-high-school-graduates-article-1.2250427]</ref>\n\nDancers in the clubs have the legal status of [[independent contractor]]s or \"space tenants.\"\n\n==Awards==\n*1998 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-1998|title= The 1998 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140626011223/http://edpublications.com/award-winners-1998|archive-date= 2014-06-26|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n*1999 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club of the Year (Midwest Nude Clubs) \u2013 [[Lansing]], [[Michigan]]<ref name=EDA1999>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-1999|title= The 1999 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*1999 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club of the Year (Southwest Nude Clubs) \u2013 [[Ontario, California]]<ref name=EDA1999/>\n*1999 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Industry Innovator of the Year \u2013 [[Harry Mohney]]<ref name=EDA1999/>\n*2000 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2000|title= The 2000 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2001 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref name=EDA2001>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2001|title= The 2001 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2001 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club of the Year (Northwest Topless and Nude Clubs) \u2013 [[Seattle, Washington]]<ref name=EDA2001/>\n*2002 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2002|title= The 2002 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2003 Exotic Dancer Hall of Fame \u2013 [[Harry Mohney]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2003|title= The 2003 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2004 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2004|title= The 2004 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications}}</ref>\n*2006 Exotic Dancer Award \u2013 Club Chain of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edpublications.com/award-winners-2006|title= The 2006 Award Winners|accessdate= 2014-08-21|publisher= ED Publications|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140626005531/http://edpublications.com/award-winners-2006|archive-date= 2014-0